# Privacy Lanes Rule

**Ownership does NOT override privacy scope.** Data belongs to one of three lanes; permissions follow the lane.

## Key Rule

Ask **"What lane does this data belong to?"** — not "Who owns the property?"
Every record: property/management | tenant | guest. Permissions follow the lane, not ownership.

## Personal Mode vs Business Mode

Users can switch modes, but privacy rules still apply. Switching to personal mode does NOT unlock tenant-private information.
- Business: owner/manager manages properties and units.
- Personal: user manages own residence or personal property.

## Business Mode (owners/managers)

In business mode (`X-Context-Mode: business`), owners and managers can see:
- Properties, unit status (occupied/vacant/unknown), Shield Mode, billing
- Property-level audits (no tenant guest events), property assignments
- Tenant invitation status at property level, management activity

They cannot see tenant guest activity (invites, names, stays, agreements, logs).

## Tenant Lane (personal mode)

Tenants see only their own guest invites, stays, overstays, agreements, authorization history. Private to tenant; owners/managers never see it.

## Guest Lane

Guests see only their own authorization record, agreement, stay status. They cannot see property or other users.

## Implementation

- Use `app/services/privacy_lanes.py` for lane detection:
  - `is_tenant_lane_invitation(db, inv)` — True if inviter has role tenant
  - `is_tenant_lane_stay(db, stay)` — True if stay is from tenant-invited guest
  - `filter_property_lane_*` — Exclude tenant-lane from owner/manager views
  - `filter_tenant_lane_from_ledger_rows(db, rows)` — Exclude tenant-lane from logs

- Owner/manager invitations and stays: return `[]` in business mode; in personal mode filter to property-lane only.
- Owner/manager logs: exclude tenant-lane events.
- When displaying guest names to owners/managers or on public pages: anonymize tenant-lane as "Guest" or "Occupied".

## Why This Simplifies

- UI decisions become obvious
- Permissions become predictable
- Privacy rules stay correct
- Development becomes much easier
